nt woman has a strong desire to eat sour or salty foods, but this has not been scientifically proven to this day. Abdominalization: Abdominal placement is one of the common signs that can determine the gender of the newborn, if it is the subject of Fetus of the uterus in the lower parts, this breast implies a pregnancy Bold. Personality and mood changes: The gender of the fetus mostly affects some behavioral changes, and it is likely that a woman who changes her personality to become aggressive, bold and dominant in her pregnancy may be pregnant with a child, and these behavior changes can be linked to testosterone levels. Urine color: It appears that a change in urine color during pregnancy to darker may be one of the signs of pregnancy with a child. Breast size: During pregnancy, the breast enlarges and increases in size in preparation for supplying the baby with milk, but some old beliefs say that increasing the right breast size is a sign of pregnancy with a child, but this matter does not have any scientific evidence. Cold limbs: The constant feeling of the coldness of the foot or hand during pregnancy is one of the indicators of pregnancy with a proven child in the beliefs of Chinese medicine. Hair growth: the rate of hair growth usually increases to faster if the gender of the fetus is male. Sleeping position: During pregnancy, the pregnant woman often feels tired and easily tired, and in this case the pregnant woman sleeps for long periods of time, and if the pregnant woman sleeps on the left side, this may be a sign of pregnancy with a child. Dry hands: Some people think dry skin, especially exfoliating skin and hands, is a sign of a bold pregnancy. Weight gain: The concentration of excess weight in a pregnant woman indicates the gender of the newborn significantly, as the concentration of obesity in the abdomen and stomach is considered a sign of pregnancy with a child, while weight gain is distributed throughout the entire body as a sign of pregnancy for a female.","Challenges: Child mortality has decreased in most countries during the past decades, however, maternal and newborn deaths have remained largely the same. Newborn deaths account for nearly 40 percent of an estimated 9.7 million deaths of children under five years of age. About 60 percent of infant deaths under one year of age. This means that the risk of a child dying on the first day of life is about 500 times greater than the risk of dying at the age of one month. The largest absolute number of birth deaths occurs in South Asia - India contributes a quarter of the global total - but the highest national birth rates are found in sub-Saharan Africa. A common factor in these deaths is maternal health. More than 500,000 women die each year during childbirth or due to complications during pregnancy. The chances of death for children whose mothers die during childbirth are much greater in the first year of life than for children whose mothers survive. Ninety-nine per cent (99 per cent) of maternal and newborn deaths occur in the developing world, where more than 50 per cent of women still give birth without the assistance of trained health workers. This is a strong example of inequity and access to quality care. Eighty per cent of maternal deaths occur as a result of direct obstetric causes such as bleeding, infection, high blood pressure in pregnancy and complications of unsafe abortion. For every woman who dies from complications related to childbirth, about 20 other women suffer from injuries, infections and disabilities that are usually not treated and ignored, and this can lead to life-long pain and social and economic exclusion. The majority of these complications are unpredictable and preventable. All pregnant women are at risk and complications can occur at any time during pregnancy, childbirth and after childbirth. However, women and families can learn how to avoid a desired pregnancy, and if pregnancy occurs, they can learn the importance of receiving prenatal care, how to recognize signs of risk, plan for emergency referral, and make safe options at birth. When problems occur, and referrals are made in a timely manner, complications can be addressed in health facilities adequately equipped with supplies and medicines, which employ a full staff of trained and skilled health workers. The solutions: Improving the health and nutrition of future mothers and providing good reproductive health services are essential in addressing the underlying causes of many child deaths. With about 50 percent of newborn deaths occurring within 24 hours of birth, and up to 75 percent per week First after birth, strategies must focus on a continuous care approach. This approach includes improving access to antenatal care during pregnancy, improving management of the natural delivery process by skilled birth attendants, access to emergency obstetric care and postpartum care when needed, and providing timely postpartum care for both mothers and newborns. In addition to strengthening links between different levels of care in health facilities, continuous care also indicates strengthening ties between society and health facilities. It is not true to assume that high-cost newborn care units in hospitals are the only way to treat sick newborns. There is now evidence to demonstrate that a large proportion of newborn deaths and diseases can be reduced by implementing simple, low-cost interventions during childbirth, during the critical first days and the first week after birth, in institutions and at home. These basic interventions include drying the baby and keeping the baby warm. Begin breastfeeding as soon as possible after birth and support the mother to make exclusive breastfeeding, give special care to low-weight babies at birth, and diagnose and treat birth problems such as suffocation and poisoning. Most of the basic interventions represent care practices that families can provide themselves. Families can also hire local health workers who can be present at birth to care for newborns and / or visit once within the first 24 hours, and one or two additional times during the first week. Where more than 50 percent of newborn deaths occur at home, the long-term goal of training enough numbers of midwives to attend all births will not be a reality in many countries for years to come. Experts estimate that providing these basic interventions widely (more than 90 percent of coverage) in society and in health facilities can reduce birth mortality rates by 70 percent. Over the past decade, UNICEF has adopted a comprehensive rights-based vision of maternal health. To this end, UNICEF works to strengthen the role of women, prevent child marriage, increase girls' education and education, eliminate female genital mutilation and support the development of life skills for adolescents. UNICEF supports improving prenatal care and immunization against tetanus, providing ITNs, intermittent preventive treatment, nutrition, preventing mother-to-child transmission of HIV, and increasing women's access to HIV treatment. Depending on the country’s needs, UNICEF also supports the training of skilled birth attendants and emergency obstetric care programs, and more recently, supports the improvement of newborn and postnatal care initiatives. Recent evidence, illustrated in the Lancet series on child survival (2003), and neonatal survival (2005) has been revealed. , And maternal survival (2006) and reproductive health (2006), a package of interventions, if implemented on a large scale, would significantly reduce","Sports are a major part of children's school life. But did you know that your child’s needs for food increase when exercising? Here are some essential nutrients that play an important role in your child's athletic performance: Starches: Starches are the main source of energy for the body as they must constitute half or more of what your child consumes in sports. Also, its food should contain mostly slow-absorbing starches that are found in bread, pasta, rice and potatoes because they provide a stable level of blood sugar to be a continuous and slow source of energy for exercise. Sports activity lasts for long hours, at which time it is preferable for your child to drink sugary drinks, which are found in sports drinks, frequently every 15-20 minutes, which preserves the stores of sugars in both muscles and the liver. Protein: Sports benefit the body building muscle, so you need protein. Your athlete needs about 1 - 1.2 g protein for every kg of weight, which can be secured if his food contains 10 - 15% of the proteins. A fundamental point must be taken into account in the child's food, which is the diversification of protein sources, which should include animal and plant proteins, so its food is not limited to vegetables, but it must also eat meat, eggs, milk and its derivatives as well. If your child, for example, had a cup of milk and an egg for breakfast, vegetables with meat alongside rice for lunch, and a sandwich of cheese for dinner, he would have had his full need of protein. Fat: As for the fatty substances, they must constitute 25-30% of the total food for your child. Sport increases the consumption of fat in the body, especially in the sport in which a simple or medium effort is made, such as what children practice continuously, and the consumption of body fat increases as long as the duration of exercise The longest. So an athlete needs a moderate amount of fat, especially from plant sources such as olive oil, olives, nuts and avocado. Tips for athletes: Eat a meal 2 - 3 hours before exercise. Drink water while exercising. Drink sugary drinks during long-term exercise. Eat slow-absorbing sugars between exercise. “Parents must help mothers preserve the child.","Parents must help mothers preserve the child."]
    
    
